May 5, 2026 Earnings Call... BOMBSHELL</h3><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Today=
 Strategy released its Q1 2026 results and held its earnings call. They now=
 hold a record 818,334 Bitcoin (worth about $64 billion at current prices).=
 They bought a lot more BTC this year using money raised from selling new s=
hares and especially their new preferred stock product called STRC.</p><h2>=
BOMBSHELL</h2><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Michael Saylor and CEO Phong Le ar=
e openly talking about strategically selling small amounts of Bitcoin =E2=
=80=94 not as a last resort or panic move, but as a normal, planned tool to=
 help pay dividends on their preferred stock (especially STRC).</p><p style=
=3D"margin:10px 0">This is a noticeable change in tone. For years Saylor ha=
mmered "we will never sell Bitcoin." Now they're saying things like:</p><ul=
><li><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">They'll sell BTC "when it's advantageous to=
 the company."</p></li><li><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">They might sell a lit=
tle "just to inoculate the market" and prove they have options.</p></li><li=
><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">They have a math model (they call it the "BTC b=
reakeven ARR") where, if Bitcoin grows even modestly (around 2%+ per year i=
n their example), they can sell tiny bits of BTC to pay dividends and still=
 end up with more Bitcoin overall =E2=80=94 as long as they keep issuing ne=
w preferred stock fast enough.</p></li></ul><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">They=
're basically saying: "We have multiple levers (sell new common stock, sell=
 more STRC preferred, use cash reserves, or sell a little BTC). We're not l=
ocked into one path anymore."</p><h3>Yes and Rem They Did Sell Bitcoin Befo=
re =E2=80=94 But Only for Taxes</h3><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Back in Dece=
mber 2022 they sold a small batch (~704 BTC) at a loss specifically to harv=
est tax losses and offset gains elsewhere. They immediately bought even mor=
e BTC back. It was a pure tax optimization move (crypto isn't subject to th=
e same "wash sale" rules as stocks). </p><h2>Here's the tax trick they're u=
sing (I reckon)</h2><ul><li><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Strategy tells inves=
tors (and the IRS via Form 8937) that they expect zero accumulated earnings=
 &amp; profits (E&amp;P) for the foreseeable future =E2=80=94 possibly 10+ =
years.</p></li><li><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Because of that, the monthly =
distributions on STRC (and their other preferred) are treated as Return of =
Capital (ROC) =E2=80=94 not taxable income right now. It just reduces your =
cost basis in the shares.</p></li></ul><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">This is a=
 huge selling point for income investors.</p><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">If =
Strategy starts selling Bitcoin at a profit (which they almost certainly wo=
uld, given their low average cost basis), those gains create taxable earnin=
gs. That creates E&amp;P. Once you have E&amp;P, the preferred dividends st=
op being nice tax-deferred ROC and start getting taxed as regular dividends=
=2E</p><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">So the=
 company is kind of boxed in:</p><ul>=
<li><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Keep issuing tons of new stock/preferred for=
ever =E2=86=92 heavy dilution, but preserve the ROC tax treatment.</p></li>=
<li><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Or sell some BTC to fund things more cleanly=
 =E2=86=92 more flexible, but risk blowing up the tax story that makes STRC=
 attractive.</p></li></ul><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Saylor &amp; team are =
trying to thread the needle by saying they'll only do small, strategic sale=
s when it still grows their Bitcoin holdings overall. They're laying the gr=
oundwork now so it doesn't shock the market later.</p><h3>Is This "Desperat=
ion"?</h3><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">No it's more like maturing the model. =
Will the market understand? Some may not get it.  </p><p style=3D"margin:10=
px 0">Rem in LIFE NEVER SAY NEVER - unless you really mean it. </p><p></p><=
/div></td></tr>
